        body: "**Cap Table Basics**\n\nCap table = Capitalization table (who owns what % of company)\n\nSimple example (at founding):\n- Founder A: 500,000 shares\n- Founder B: 500,000 shares\n- Total: 1,000,000 shares\n\nOwnership:\n- Founder A: 50%\n- Founder B: 50%\n\nSeed round: Investor wants 20% for £500k\n- Investor needs: 250,000 shares (to have 250k / 1.25M = 20%)\n- New cap table:\n  - Founder A: 500k shares (40%)\n  - Founder B: 500k shares (40%)\n  - Seed investor: 250k shares (20%)\n  - Total: 1.25M shares\n\nDilution: Founders went from 50% each → 40% each (10% dilution)\n\n**Series A Dilution**\n\nBefore Series A:\n- Founder A: 40%\n- Founder B: 40%\n- Seed investor: 20%\n- Total shares: 1.25M\n\nSeries A: New VC wants 25% for £3M\n- New VC needs: 417k shares (to have 417k / 1.667M = 25%)\n- New cap table:\n  - Founder A: 500k shares (30%)\n  - Founder B: 500k shares (30%)\n  - Seed investor: 250k shares (15%)\n  - Series A VC: 417k shares (25%)\n  - Total: 1.667M shares\n\nDilution: Founders went from 40% → 30% each (10% dilution each)\nSeed investor went from 20% → 15% (5% dilution)\nNew VC: 25%\n\n**Multi-Round Dilution Pattern**\n\nTypical progression:\n\nSeed (£500k for 20%):\n- Founders: 80% → Diluted 20%\n\nSeries A (£3M for 25%):\n- Founders: 80% × 75% = 60%\n- Seed: 20% × 75% = 15%\n- Series A: 25%\n\nSeries B (£10M for 40%):\n- Founders: 60% × 60% = 36%\n- Seed: 15% × 60% = 9%\n- Series A: 25% × 60% = 15%\n- Series B: 40%\n\nSeries C (£30M for 40%):\n- Founders: 36% × 60% = 21.6%\n- Seed: 9% × 60% = 5.4%\n- Series A: 15% × 60% = 9%\n- Series B: 15% × 60% = 9%\n- Series C: 40%\n\nFinal: Founders own 21.6% of company (started at 100%)\n\nBut company value: £500k (seed) → £2M (Series A post) → £25M (Series B post) → £62.5M (Series C post)\n\nFounder equity value: 100% of £500k = £500k → 60% of £25M = £15M → 21.6% of £62.5M = £13.5M\n\nNote: Ownership dilutes but value increases 25x (from £500k to £13.5M)\n\n**Option Pools and Anti-Dilution**\n\nOption pool: Reserve shares for employees (vested over 4 years, cliff at 1 year)\n\nWithout pool:\n- Series A at 25% dilution (investors take 25%, founders split 75%)\n- By Series B, 30% more dilution (investors take 30%, founders now 52.5%)\n- Founders diluted 47.5% total (steep)\n\nWith 15% pool:\n- Seed round: 15% set aside for options, 85% to founders + seed investor\n- Series A: Investor wants 25% (from the 85% pool, not creating new dilution)\n- Series B: Investor wants 30% (again, from existing pool, less dilution)\n- Founders diluted: Less (because pool was carved out upfront)\n\nTrick: Option pool is usually carved out of founder equity (not investor equity)\n\nExample without smart pool:\n- Founders: 100% → Series A dilutes to 75% (to give investor 25%)\n- Then create 15% option pool (now founders are 60%, investor 25%, pool 15%)\n- Net dilution: 40% (bad)\n\nExample with smart pool:\n- Create 15% option pool upfront (founders 85%, pool 15%)\n- Series A investor gets 25% of company (dilutes everyone proportionally)\n- Founders: 85% × 75% = 63.75%, Investor: 25%, Pool: 11.25%\n- Net dilution: 21.25% (better)\n\n**Fully-Diluted Ownership**\n\nImportant: Track fully-diluted ownership (what you own if all options are exercised)\n\nExample post-Series B:\n- Shares outstanding: 10M\n- Founder shares: 3.6M (36% of outstanding)\n- Options outstanding: 1.5M (option pool)\n\nFully-diluted:\n- Total shares if options exercised: 10M + 1.5M = 11.5M\n- Founder ownership: 3.6M / 11.5M = 31.3% (not 36%!)\n\nWhy matters: Decision-making\n- For dilution purposes: 31.3% (realistic control)\n- For liquidation: 36% (of proceeds, but option holders also benefit)\n\n**Anti-Dilution Clauses**\n\nProtection for early investors (Seed investor holds 20%, wants to not be diluted below 15%)\n\nDownside scenario:\n- Seed investor: 20%\n- Series A comes in and asks for 25%\n- Normally: Seed investor diluted to 15%, Founder diluted to 60%\n- With anti-dilution: Seed investor gets more shares (anti-dilute adjustment)\n- Result: Founder diluted even more (60% → 55%)\n\nWhy? Seed investor protected their ownership percentage (can't go below 15%)\n\nTypes:\n- Weighted average: Most common (partial protection)\n- Full ratchet: Rare (excessive protection, kills companies)\n\nFor founders: Negotiate to avoid strong anti-dilution (costs them heavily in down rounds)\n\n**Cap Table Best Practices**\n\n✅ Set 15-20% option pool before Series A (carved from founder equity)\n✅ Track fully-diluted ownership (include option pool)\n✅ Understand each investor's anti-dilution clause\n✅ Model dilution ahead (Series A, B, C projections)\n✅ Consider secondary sales for early investors (lets them get liquidity without dilution)\n\n❌ Don't wait until Series A to create option pool (costs founders more)\n❌ Don't assume ownership % = control (track fully-diluted)\n❌ Don't accept weighted average anti-dilution >1x (limits your fundraising)"
