        body: "**Price Elasticity Basics**\n\nElasticity = How much volume changes when price changes\n\nExample:\n- Current: £100/month, 100 customers\n- Test: £110/month, show to next 100 new customers\n- Result: 95 customers (5% fewer at higher price)\n- Elasticity: -0.5 (5% volume change / 10% price change)\n\nImpact on revenue:\n- Current: 100 × £100 = £10,000\n- Test: 95 × £110 = £10,450\n- Change: +£450 (+4.5% revenue)\n\nConclusion: Raise price (revenue up despite fewer customers)\n\n**Testing Framework**\n\nStep 1: Identify test cell\n- Which customers to test on?\n- Option A: New customers (don't annoy existing)\n- Option B: Existing cohorts (if testing tier upgrade)\n- Option C: Geographic subset (if testing regional pricing)\n- Recommendation: New customers (cleanest test)\n\nStep 2: Design variants\n- Control: Current price (baseline)\n- Variant 1: Price +5%\n- Variant 2: Price +10%\n- Variant 3: Price +15% (optional, if want aggressive test)\n- Don't test more than 2-3 variants (confusing, harder to achieve significance)\n\nStep 3: Run test\n- Duration: Until 50-100 customers in each variant (statistical power)\n- Timeline: If 20 customers/month → 2.5 months per variant\n- If 100 customers/month → 0.5 months per variant\n- Randomize: 50% control, 50% variant (ensure comparable customers)\n\nStep 4: Measure\n- Conversion rate: % of visitors → customers\n- Revenue per customer: Average price paid\n- LTV: Lifetime value (if expansion tracked)\n- Churn: Does price affect retention?\n\nExample results:\n\nControl (£100):\n- Conversion: 5%\n- Revenue per customer: £100\n- LTV: £1,000\n- Churn: 3% monthly\n\nVariant (+10% = £110):\n- Conversion: 4.7% (-0.3%)\n- Revenue per customer: £110\n- LTV: £1,100 (if churn same)\n- Churn: 3% monthly (same)\n\nAnalysis:\n- Conversion down slightly (-0.3%, within noise if n=100)\n- Revenue per customer up 10%\n- LTV up 10%\n- Churn same (price didn't affect stickiness)\n- Net: Raise price (better revenue)\n\n**Multi-Variant Testing (Advanced)**\n\nTest presentation AND price:\n\nVariant 1: £100/month (current)\nVariant 2: £1,200/year (same as £100/month, but annual emphasis)\nVariant 3: £1,080/year (10% discount for annual commitment)\nVariant 4: £110/month (direct price increase)\n\nExpected results:\n- Variant 1 (monthly emphasis): Baseline 5% conversion\n- Variant 2 (annual emphasis, same price): 6% conversion (+20%, anchoring effect)\n- Variant 3 (annual discount): 7% conversion (+40%, incentivizes commitment)\n- Variant 4 (price increase): 4% conversion (-20%, loses price-sensitive customers)\n\nConclusion: Offer annual at 10% discount (Variant 3) = higher conversion + better unit economics\n\n**Pricing Tiers A/B Testing**\n\nCurrent tiers:\n- Starter: £50/month, 40% of customers\n- Pro: £150/month, 50% of customers\n- Enterprise: Custom, 10% of customers\n\nTest: Add mid-tier\n- Starter: £50/month\n- Professional: £100/month (NEW)\n- Pro: £150/month (moved)\n- Enterprise: Custom\n\nExpected impact:\n- Some Starter customers upgrade to Professional (£50 → £100)\n- Some Pro customers drop to Professional (£150 → £100)\n- Net: Shift in mix, overall revenue impact varies\n- Measure: Total revenue per cohort\n\nResult:\n- Control (3 tiers): £10k MRR from 100 customers\n- Test (4 tiers): £10.5k MRR from 100 customers\n- Conclusion: Mid-tier working (captures willingness to pay between £50-£150)\n\n**Statistical Significance**\n\nWhy it matters: With small sample size, differences are noise\n\nExample:\n- Control: 100 customers, 5% conversion = 5 conversions\n- Variant: 100 customers, 5.3% conversion = 5.3 conversions\n- Difference: 0.3% (could be random chance)\n\nRule of thumb: Need n=50+ per variant to trust 1-2% differences\n\nIf seeing <50 customers/month: Test not viable (would take too long)\n\nAlternatives: Use pricing psychology (anchor, decoy) instead of testing\n\n**Quick Pricing Tests (No Waiting)**\n\nIf can't do classic A/B test (not enough volume):\n\n1. Survey pricing: Ask 20 potential customers \"What would you pay?\"\n   - Van Westendorp method (4 price questions)\n   - Estimate willingness to pay\n   - Fast (1 week)\n   - Less accurate than A/B test\n\n2. Conjoint analysis: Show different feature combinations + prices\n   - Measure: What features customers value most?\n   - Calculate: Optimal price for each feature set\n   - Fast (2 weeks)\n   - Moderately accurate\n\n3. Pricing psychology tricks (no test needed):\n   - Anchoring: Show high price first (anchors perception)\n   - Decoy pricing: Add \"bad value\" tier (makes others look good)\n   - Payment frequency: £1,200/year cheaper than £100/month\n\n**A/B Testing Pitfalls**\n\n❌ Testing too many variants\n- Confuses results\n- Takes longer to get significance\n- Fix: Test 2 variants at a time\n\n❌ Stopping test early\n- See good results, stop and declare winner\n- But small n = false positive\n- Fix: Run until n=50+ per variant\n\n❌ Testing non-comparable customers\n- Group A: Enterprise-focused → high conversion\n- Group B: SMB-focused → low conversion\n- Can't compare (different customers, not prices)\n- Fix: Randomize customers across variants\n\n❌ Not tracking churn\n- Price might increase conversion but decrease retention\n- Net LTV could be lower despite higher price\n- Fix: Track churn rate in test (compare LTV, not just conversion)"
